Former Senate Republican Leader Robert J. Dole received the Congressional Gold Medal, the highest award a civilian can receive from Congress. Dole, now 94 years old, is recognized for his decades-long political career and his service in the Army during World War II. He holds the record for longest-serving Republican leader in the Senate and is known for his bipartisan work on issues such as Social Security. Dole has also been involved in various philanthropic efforts, including raising funds for the World War II Memorial and the Families of Freedom Scholarship Fund. He founded The Robert J. Dole Institute of Politics at the University of Kansas in 2003. President Trump recognized Dole for his involvement in making the World War II Memorial a reality. Dole's example of leadership and determination serves as a role model for both inside and outside of politics.